Miller's Crossing is so fucking good, the way the Coens are able to maintain tension and weave as they see fit, leaving Tom's fate and his constant gambling with his plans in the air up until the last possible second is something, and to that so early in their career? These guys are just an example of how studying the greats and putting your own stamp on it goes along way to making a great film and they're certainly the giants of American cinema.

I also marvel at the fact how they took that motorbreath delivery that's seen as a staple of noir/mobster films and made it their own with their own brand of wry humor they're known as. I've been ignoring their opus for years now only having seen Lebowski, Fargo and NCFOM, but recently I've been going through their filmography and I am really impressed by the sheer quality of their output, they overshadow their duds no question about it. And those slick references to Barton Fink are neat, I love shit like that!

Anyway, /tv/, what's the rumpus on Miller's Crossing, you chewing over it or you a potato eater?

Jake Sully adopts Quaritch’s son, aka Spider
Quaritch returns as a recom and serves the RDA for the entire film, he does clash with a new colonel who reminded me of that pink haired woman from The Last Jedi
Neytiri doesn’t die, although her role in the story has been reduced, her children take primary focus
Sigourney Weaver returns as Na’vi jailbait, although it’s left ambiguous whether she’s Dr, Augustine’s reincarnation or an entirely new character (same thing goes with the new Quaritch)
Recom Quaritch finds his old human corpse left in the aftermath of the first film. He collects his own skull and keeps it as a memento
Recom Quaritch captures Spider in order to uncover the location of Jake’s base, they arrive to find it abandoned. It’s around this time that Quaritch finally realises that he’s found his son, he grows distant and ventures into some caves alone. Wherein he examines his human skull and crushes it
Jake and company migrate to a new Na’vi tribe who live beside on a tropical seashore, Jake basically forces the tribe to take them in by invoking an ancient tradition. They are begrudgingly accepted
This tropical region is notable for being subject to frequent eclipses, the tribe worship these sudden moments of darkness as…the way of water
